Because it really challenges,
not the rest of what

00:24:50.490 --> 00:24:53.590 align:middle line:84%
we've done-- a lot of normal
science still stands--

00:24:53.590 --> 00:24:57.190 align:middle line:84%
but I think if you're looking
at the intention work,

00:24:57.190 --> 00:25:00.030 align:middle line:84%
it does affect our
scientific method

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:01.480 align:middle line:90%
and how we design experiments.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:03.210 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, I just
started thinking,

00:25:03.210 --> 00:25:04.980 align:middle line:90%
this is really important.

00:25:04.980 --> 00:25:06.150 align:middle line:90%
And we're not looking at it.

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:07.120 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you're
not looking at it.

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:08.995 align:middle line:84%
And then you started
meeting with some people

00:25:08.995 --> 00:25:10.985 align:middle line:84%
fairly high up in
the government.

00:25:10.985 --> 00:25:12.810 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: So yeah,
Hal connected me

00:25:12.810 --> 00:25:16.270 align:middle line:84%
with various different
people that he knew.

00:25:16.270 --> 00:25:18.520 align:middle line:90%
And I just spoke to them.

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:22.700 align:middle line:84%
Each person that I spoke to
was another crisis for me.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:26.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because it opened up
a new can of worms of research,

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:29.880 align:middle line:90%
understanding, experience.

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:33.630 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: Everything that they
said, every word, every topic, I

00:25:33.630 --> 00:25:35.550 align:middle line:90%
had never heard of before.

00:25:35.550 --> 00:25:38.890 align:middle line:90%
So it's stuff all over Gaia now.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:40.770 align:middle line:84%
But it's things that I
had never encountered.

00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And so I would just take
notes and sit there wide-eyed

00:25:43.020 --> 00:25:44.260 align:middle line:90%
and just listen.

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:48.150 align:middle line:84%
But after every call, I
would sob on the floor

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:50.260 align:middle line:84%
because I was like, I
don't understand anything.

00:25:50.260 --> 00:25:50.765 align:middle line:90%
What's happening?

00:25:50.765 --> 00:25:52.770 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It made you
feel like you knew nothing

00:25:52.770 --> 00:25:54.350 align:middle line:84%
in the face of
everything, right?

00:25:54.350 --> 00:25:55.150 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:59.290 align:middle line:84%
And then, I mean, also, some
of it is just really weird.

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:03.270 align:middle line:84%
And so you're like, oh, is
reality really this weird?

00:26:03.270 --> 00:26:06.790 align:middle line:90%
Or like, what is the truth?

00:26:06.790 --> 00:26:11.990 align:middle line:84%
And if so, it's a
little upsetting

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:14.450 align:middle line:84%
if you're coming
from just mainstream

00:26:14.450 --> 00:26:18.590 align:middle line:84%
science and normal
life to, in some ways,

00:26:18.590 --> 00:26:20.010 align:middle line:90%
you don't want to know about.

00:26:20.010 --> 00:26:23.450 align:middle line:84%
I felt I started to feel like
I wish I didn't know about some

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:24.250 align:middle line:90%
of this stuff.

00:26:24.250 --> 00:26:25.050 align:middle line:90%
I wish--

00:26:25.050 --> 00:26:26.663 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Give us
an example of what

00:26:26.663 --> 00:26:28.580 align:middle line:84%
really disturbed you
because you just couldn't

00:26:28.580 --> 00:26:30.325 align:middle line:90%
get your mind around it.

00:26:30.325 --> 00:26:33.050 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: The
dimensions and, maybe,

00:26:33.050 --> 00:26:36.920 align:middle line:84%
beings in other dimensions
and their ability

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:40.760 align:middle line:84%
to maybe come in and out of
ours, that was upsetting to me.

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:42.150 align:middle line:90%
I wish I didn't know about that.

00:26:42.150 --> 00:26:44.025 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's upsetting
to a lot of people

00:26:44.025 --> 00:26:46.820 align:middle line:84%
when they first encountered that
information even if you're not

00:26:46.820 --> 00:26:48.310 align:middle line:90%
a scientist.

00:26:48.310 --> 00:26:49.782 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:26:49.782 --> 00:26:51.240 align:middle line:84%
No, it was really
more as a person.

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:52.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:52.920 --> 00:26:57.750 align:middle line:84%
I was like, I don't know
that I want to know this.

00:26:57.750 --> 00:26:58.650 align:middle line:90%
It was frightening.

00:26:58.650 --> 00:27:02.450 align:middle line:84%
But it settled, I
think, initially,

00:27:02.450 --> 00:27:04.230 align:middle line:90%
and then you get used to it.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:05.030 align:middle line:90%
And it's settled.

00:27:05.030 --> 00:27:06.738 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Did you
ultimately come across,

00:27:06.738 --> 00:27:08.700 align:middle line:84%
I assume, the concepts
of parallel timelines

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:10.120 align:middle line:90%
and that time is not linear?

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:10.920 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:27:10.920 --> 00:27:12.337 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: How did
that affect you?

00:27:12.337 --> 00:27:15.360 align:middle line:84%
Because that's one that
I think most people still

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:17.880 align:middle line:84%
grapple with a bit
because it's hard to get

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:19.680 align:middle line:90%
our linear minds around.

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:22.390 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: That one actually
made more sense to me.

00:27:22.390 --> 00:27:23.796 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure why.

00:27:23.796 --> 00:27:25.990 align:middle line:90%
And it excited me.

00:27:25.990 --> 00:27:27.160 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was exciting.

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:32.610 align:middle line:84%
I thought, that's cool if
you can affect the past

00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:34.500 align:middle line:90%
from the present or the future.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:35.530 align:middle line:90%
Or I don't know.

00:27:35.530 --> 00:27:36.560 align:middle line:84%
I just thought it
was really exciting.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:38.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so that was
more comfortable for you?

00:27:38.730 --> 00:27:39.530 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:42.243 align:middle line:84%
And I think probably because of
the coffee readings with my mom

00:27:42.243 --> 00:27:43.410 align:middle line:90%
because I had already seen--

00:27:43.410 --> 00:27:44.175 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You
already experienced.

00:27:44.175 --> 00:27:45.633 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah,
that might be why.

00:27:45.633 --> 00:27:46.440 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hmm.

00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:51.210 align:middle line:84%
So ultimately,
after interviewing

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:55.050 align:middle line:84%
all of these people,
what to you was the most

00:27:55.050 --> 00:27:57.960 align:middle line:90%
shocking and powerful--

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:00.540 align:middle line:84%
and I know it's hard to
answer-- bit of evidence

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:04.120 align:middle line:84%
that you came across that if
you had just 15 seconds to say,

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:05.910 align:middle line:84%
this thing rocked
your world when

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:08.700 align:middle line:84%
you were doing this research,
what would that have been?

00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:14.106 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: I think maybe the
consciousness surviving death.

00:28:14.106 --> 00:28:15.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Reincarnation?

00:28:15.210 --> 00:28:18.680 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: Maybe yes,
which is related to that.

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:19.790 align:middle line:90%
It survives death.

00:28:19.790 --> 00:28:26.330 align:middle line:84%
And then, yeah, that, I
actually believe it now.

00:28:26.330 --> 00:28:28.430 align:middle line:84%
I think I believe
that it's possible.

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:33.710 align:middle line:10%
I think that one really shook
me because, as a neuroscientist,

00:28:33.710 --> 00:28:37.450 align:middle line:10%
we're taught that the
brain, the physical matter

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:40.430 align:middle line:10%
of the brain, the neurons,
produce consciousness.

00:28:40.430 --> 00:28:43.220 align:middle line:10%
And so if there was no brain,
there would be no consciousness.

00:28:43.220 --> 00:28:47.420 align:middle line:10%
And this is really driven home.

00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:50.290 align:middle line:84%
So when I started
doing this research,

00:28:50.290 --> 00:28:54.710 align:middle line:84%
I didn't encounter that
theory until a few months in.

00:28:54.710 --> 00:28:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And when I did, I was
immediately like, no,

00:28:58.540 --> 00:28:59.730 align:middle line:90%
that is not possible.

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:02.230 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, because that
was strictly against everything

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:02.840 align:middle line:90%
you were taught.

00:29:02.840 --> 00:29:04.880 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: I was like,
that's just not possible.

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:07.660 align:middle line:84%
But what it took was
me reading philosophy

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:11.690 align:middle line:84%
to understand that there
are other worldviews

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:15.100 align:middle line:84%
and to even understand
that mainstream science's

00:29:15.100 --> 00:29:18.910 align:middle line:84%
worldview is scientific
materialism or physicalism.

00:29:18.910 --> 00:29:20.540 align:middle line:90%
They don't teach you that.

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:23.740 align:middle line:84%
That's an assumption
with-- no one ever tells us

00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:25.280 align:middle line:90%
that what we're working under.

00:29:25.280 --> 00:29:27.970 align:middle line:84%
And you never learn that
there's other possibilities,

00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:31.340 align:middle line:84%
like panpsychism or
idealism or whatever.

00:29:31.340 --> 00:29:34.540 align:middle line:84%
So once I learned
that, I would say,

00:29:34.540 --> 00:29:39.040 align:middle line:84%
things rapidly turned around
because there was finally

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:45.170 align:middle line:84%
room for an explanation for
all of this that made sense.

00:29:45.170 --> 00:29:48.390 align:middle line:84%
And the consciousness didn't
have to come from the brain

00:29:48.390 --> 00:29:49.190 align:middle line:90%
anymore.

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:52.990 align:middle line:84%
So that limitation that
I had from my training,

00:29:52.990 --> 00:29:54.740 align:middle line:84%
you're just like, oh,
this is my training.

00:29:54.740 --> 00:29:56.890 align:middle line:84%
It's under scientific
materialism,

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:58.670 align:middle line:90%
but there's other philosophies.

00:29:58.670 --> 00:30:02.330 align:middle line:84%
And so if I just step outside of
that, it's perfectly reasonable.

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:05.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And then because
the areas of science

00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:08.250 align:middle line:84%
don't speak to each other,
they're not collaborating,

00:30:08.250 --> 00:30:09.750 align:middle line:84%
they're not
communicating, and you'd

00:30:09.750 --> 00:30:12.720 align:middle line:84%
think neuroscience would
be at the center of a very

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:16.500 align:middle line:84%
vast exploration about
the greater mind.

00:30:16.500 --> 00:30:17.610 align:middle line:90%
But it's not.

00:30:17.610 --> 00:30:18.460 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: It's not.

00:30:18.460 --> 00:30:19.260 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:19.600 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:19.840 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:21.590 align:middle line:84%
Neuroscience, just
like all other science,

00:30:21.590 --> 00:30:22.660 align:middle line:90%
is very specialized.

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:27.640 align:middle line:84%
We all have our niches
that we stay inside of.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:28.570 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:30:28.570 --> 00:30:32.040 align:middle line:84%
And that's going to
be drawing to a close,

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:33.280 align:middle line:90%
hopefully, pretty soon.

00:30:33.280 --> 00:30:35.080 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we'll talk
about that in a minute.

00:30:35.080 --> 00:30:38.460 align:middle line:84%
But that's one of the things
that bothered you because here

00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:40.450 align:middle line:90%
you had mental illness.

00:30:40.450 --> 00:30:42.970 align:middle line:84%
You could talk about a
break from zero point.

00:30:42.970 --> 00:30:45.640 align:middle line:84%
And this was something
that really fascinated you.

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:48.410 align:middle line:84%
And as a neuroscientist--
and there were psychologists,

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:49.660 align:middle line:90%
you never spoke to each other.

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:53.200 align:middle line:84%
You never got to look at the
whole situation with the person.

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:55.940 align:middle line:84%
Tell us a little bit about that
and what drove you on that path.

00:30:55.940 --> 00:30:57.180 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yes.

00:30:57.180 --> 00:31:02.010 align:middle line:84%
So neuroscience takes a
very reductionist view

00:31:02.010 --> 00:31:03.280 align:middle line:90%
of mental illness.

00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:06.200 align:middle line:84%
And I won't go into
the whole history.

00:31:06.200 --> 00:31:10.098 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We probably
wouldn't understand it.

00:31:10.098 --> 00:31:10.930 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:31:10.930 --> 00:31:13.483 align:middle line:84%
So it's very reductionist
and very chemical.

00:31:13.483 --> 00:31:15.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I do think people are
familiar with that, the idea

00:31:15.900 --> 00:31:19.110 align:middle line:84%
that depression is a
chemical imbalance.

00:31:19.110 --> 00:31:20.920 align:middle line:84%
That has been a narrative
for a long time.

00:31:20.920 --> 00:31:22.710 align:middle line:84%
These are all
narrative-based, they're

00:31:22.710 --> 00:31:25.470 align:middle line:84%
theories that we come
up with in the field

00:31:25.470 --> 00:31:27.745 align:middle line:90%
to explain some behavior.

00:31:27.745 --> 00:31:29.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And there's
some truth in it.

00:31:29.370 --> 00:31:32.190 align:middle line:84%
We've all heard about
dopamine and serotonin

00:31:32.190 --> 00:31:34.870 align:middle line:84%
and neurotransmitters
and neurochemicals.

00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:36.497 align:middle line:90%
We've heard these things.

00:31:36.497 --> 00:31:37.955 align:middle line:84%
It's common now to
have heard that.

00:31:37.955 --> 00:31:41.588 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: But well,
first of all, we still

00:31:41.588 --> 00:31:44.130 align:middle line:84%
don't have a good understanding,
actually, of mental illness.

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:46.020 align:middle line:84%
Because if we did,
we would probably

00:31:46.020 --> 00:31:50.200 align:middle line:84%
be better able to create
pharmaceuticals or whatever,

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:53.920 align:middle line:84%
any kind of treatment, whatever
it is that could address this.

00:31:53.920 --> 00:31:55.500 align:middle line:84%
But our treatments
for mental illness

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:57.293 align:middle line:90%
are terrible and lacking.

00:31:57.293 --> 00:32:00.895 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Terrible, basically
put a person in a stupor.

00:32:00.895 --> 00:32:03.050 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yes, yeah.

00:32:03.050 --> 00:32:06.650 align:middle line:84%
And the drugs only work, I
think, for 50% of the people,

00:32:06.650 --> 00:32:07.910 align:middle line:90%
50% of the time.

00:32:07.910 --> 00:32:10.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: There's
always lobotomy.

00:32:10.670 --> 00:32:11.845 align:middle line:90%
We do have other tools.

00:32:11.845 --> 00:32:14.530 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: It did have
its benefits, though.

00:32:14.530 --> 00:32:15.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:18.390 align:middle line:84%
So I think, yeah, we never
learned about psychology,

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:22.772 align:middle line:84%
though, and cognitive behavioral
therapy and all of those things.

00:32:22.772 --> 00:32:24.980 align:middle line:84%
Neuroscience never even
touches that, which is crazy,

00:32:24.980 --> 00:32:27.950 align:middle line:84%
to think that if you're
a neuroscientist working

00:32:27.950 --> 00:32:32.900 align:middle line:84%
on depression, I'm not sure that
you spend a lot of time looking

00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:38.300 align:middle line:84%
into behavioral therapies or
how those could maybe even work

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:41.545 align:middle line:84%
together with the chemical
model that you're using.

00:32:41.545 --> 00:32:44.090 align:middle line:90%


00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:46.760 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not
aware of, if there

00:32:46.760 --> 00:32:49.850 align:middle line:84%
are very few labs that look at
the overlap and the interplay

00:32:49.850 --> 00:32:50.670 align:middle line:90%
between them.

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:53.600 align:middle line:84%
So as a result, we don't have
good models of mental illness.

00:32:53.600 --> 00:32:55.156 align:middle line:84%
And we don't have
good treatments.

00:32:55.156 --> 00:32:55.956 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:32:55.956 --> 00:32:57.750 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to ask
you to go out on a limb

00:32:57.750 --> 00:33:01.640 align:middle line:84%
because now it seems that the
world is experiencing almost

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:03.800 align:middle line:90%
an epidemic of mental illness.

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:06.110 align:middle line:84%
And it's showing up
in a lot of ways.

00:33:06.110 --> 00:33:08.060 align:middle line:90%
Kids are being drugged.

00:33:08.060 --> 00:33:10.500 align:middle line:84%
People are living and
sleeping on the streets.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:12.380 align:middle line:84%
There's a kind of
cognitive dissonance

00:33:12.380 --> 00:33:14.670 align:middle line:84%
where people are just
floating through life.

00:33:14.670 --> 00:33:20.180 align:middle line:84%
What, with everything
you've studied,

00:33:20.180 --> 00:33:22.650 align:middle line:84%
on a multi-dimensional
level, do you

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:25.900 align:middle line:84%
consider to be feeding the
state we call mental illness?

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:27.650 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:32.030 align:middle line:10%
If I were to step back into
my old neuroscience shoes

00:33:32.030 --> 00:33:34.380 align:middle line:10%
before all this
stuff happened to me,

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:37.220 align:middle line:10%
I would despair and be like,
we have no understanding

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:40.260 align:middle line:10%
of mental illness, and we're
nowhere near understanding it.

00:33:40.260 --> 00:33:44.760 align:middle line:84%
But after this journey, I
started exploring psychology.

00:33:44.760 --> 00:33:47.728 align:middle line:84%
And I started trying all these
different treatment modalities

00:33:47.728 --> 00:33:50.270 align:middle line:84%
that I came across in the books
I was reading, like past life

00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:54.740 align:middle line:84%
regression and psychedelics
and emotional freedom technique

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:56.210 align:middle line:90%
and all these different things.

00:33:56.210 --> 00:33:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And I started to see in
myself an improvement

00:33:59.170 --> 00:34:04.550 align:middle line:84%
in emotional regulation,
understanding my own emotions,

00:34:04.550 --> 00:34:08.290 align:middle line:84%
connecting with myself,
even knowing what I want,

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:09.699 align:middle line:90%
or who I was.

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:12.460 align:middle line:84%
And I, in that
literature, found models

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:16.909 align:middle line:84%
of what goes wrong when you
lose connection with yourself,

00:34:16.909 --> 00:34:19.480 align:middle line:84%
or when you don't
address your traumas

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:22.850 align:middle line:84%
or come to be in good
relationship with your emotions.

00:34:22.850 --> 00:34:25.469 align:middle line:84%
So, I mean, as a
neuroscientist, I

00:34:25.469 --> 00:34:27.620 align:middle line:84%
would have scoffed at all
of that and been like,

00:34:27.620 --> 00:34:29.460 align:middle line:84%
no, it's chemicals, and
we'll figure it out,

00:34:29.460 --> 00:34:30.580 align:middle line:90%
the neurotransmitters.

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:36.949 align:middle line:84%
But I personally experienced the
benefit of all of those things,

00:34:36.949 --> 00:34:40.659 align:middle line:84%
And they changed
my life drastically

00:34:40.659 --> 00:34:44.600 align:middle line:84%
for the better, including
my shift in worldview.

00:34:44.600 --> 00:34:47.830 align:middle line:84%
So even flipping the worldview
to think that the universe might

00:34:47.830 --> 00:34:51.880 align:middle line:84%
not be meaningless, or that
there's no meaning to life, even

00:34:51.880 --> 00:34:55.389 align:middle line:84%
flipping that significantly
improved my quality of life.

00:34:55.389 --> 00:34:57.910 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And to be able
to, perhaps, fold into it

00:34:57.910 --> 00:35:00.180 align:middle line:84%
and, maybe, what's influencing
this person isn't even

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:01.100 align:middle line:90%
from this lifetime.

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:01.900 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Right.

00:35:01.900 --> 00:35:02.970 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Maybe it's
something embedded

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:04.680 align:middle line:90%
in the subconscious somewhere.

00:35:04.680 --> 00:35:07.836 align:middle line:84%
And science doesn't even know
how to address the subconscious.

00:35:07.836 --> 00:35:09.805 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yes, it's a lot.

00:35:09.805 --> 00:35:11.680 align:middle line:84%
Neuroscience definitely
doesn't address that.

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:14.520 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, they're starting
to with the emergence

00:35:14.520 --> 00:35:17.220 align:middle line:90%
of attachment theory.

00:35:17.220 --> 00:35:19.080 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's
popular right now.

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:20.845 align:middle line:84%
A lot of shorts
on that out there.

00:35:20.845 --> 00:35:21.970 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah, we'll see.

00:35:21.970 --> 00:35:23.410 align:middle line:90%
But that one is useful.

00:35:23.410 --> 00:35:26.910 align:middle line:84%
And it does connect the
subconscious behavior

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:29.410 align:middle line:84%
to conscious behavior
and how that plays out.

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:34.450 align:middle line:84%
So I would say, that's the
best we've gotten thus far.

00:35:34.450 --> 00:35:37.870 align:middle line:84%
And it might help connect
neuroscience and psychology.

00:35:37.870 --> 00:35:42.190 align:middle line:84%
But there has been a lot
lacking in that area.

00:35:42.190 --> 00:35:44.890 align:middle line:84%
And I think it really is like
a disconnection from ourselves,

00:35:44.890 --> 00:35:50.910 align:middle line:84%
from nature, from each other,
from a higher power, all

00:35:50.910 --> 00:35:52.407 align:middle line:90%
those things that have caused--

00:35:52.407 --> 00:35:54.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: People spending
so much time alone

00:35:54.240 --> 00:35:56.760 align:middle line:84%
in their siloed
information that it

00:35:56.760 --> 00:36:01.170 align:middle line:84%
is creating a mass cognitive
dissonance and an inability

00:36:01.170 --> 00:36:04.830 align:middle line:84%
to even look at another person
that feels differently than you

00:36:04.830 --> 00:36:07.325 align:middle line:84%
and understand them
or accept them at all.

00:36:07.325 --> 00:36:08.280 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Definitely.

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:11.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That is kind of a
low-grade mental illness where

00:36:11.730 --> 00:36:14.050 align:middle line:84%
you can't take
difference anymore.

00:36:14.050 --> 00:36:15.250 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: That's right.

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:16.270 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:36:16.270 --> 00:36:18.427 align:middle line:84%
Nobody can take-- they
can't be uncomfortable.

00:36:18.427 --> 00:36:20.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They can't
be uncomfortable.

00:36:20.010 --> 00:36:23.500 align:middle line:84%
If someone disagrees with you,
your whole body seizes up.

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And now you're in a
mild panic mode what

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:28.150 align:middle line:90%
to do with this friendship.

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:30.455 align:middle line:90%
We disagreed on something.

00:36:30.455 --> 00:36:32.400 align:middle line:84%
Right now, it seems
that we have been

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:36.476 align:middle line:84%
groomed to have very little
emotional resilience.

00:36:36.476 --> 00:36:39.310 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yes, you're right.

00:36:39.310 --> 00:36:40.720 align:middle line:90%
I completely agree with that.

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:41.700 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:43.830 align:middle line:84%
It's like, if something
makes you uncomfortable

00:36:43.830 --> 00:36:48.000 align:middle line:84%
or triggers you, you just shut
it down, walk out, walk away

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:49.080 align:middle line:90%
from it.

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:51.710 align:middle line:84%
But I learned in a
lot of the research

00:36:51.710 --> 00:36:55.040 align:middle line:84%
that I was doing, even though it
started off spiritual and then

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:58.550 align:middle line:84%
quickly became healing
work and psychological,

00:36:58.550 --> 00:37:03.950 align:middle line:84%
that you came here to allegedly
work through this stuff

00:37:03.950 --> 00:37:05.010 align:middle line:90%
to feel it all.

00:37:05.010 --> 00:37:08.810 align:middle line:84%
And the only way
to really heal is

00:37:08.810 --> 00:37:10.440 align:middle line:90%
to feel it and work through it.

00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:14.240 align:middle line:84%
So, I mean, I started doing
that even though it was hard.

00:37:14.240 --> 00:37:16.640 align:middle line:84%
I was very avoidant
initially, so

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:20.390 align:middle line:84%
out of touch with my
emotions, very repressed.

00:37:20.390 --> 00:37:22.220 align:middle line:84%
And part of that is
science because you

00:37:22.220 --> 00:37:24.470 align:middle line:84%
have to put on this
persona of being

00:37:24.470 --> 00:37:29.310 align:middle line:84%
very hard and serious and
unemotional and objective.

00:37:29.310 --> 00:37:33.650 align:middle line:84%
And that really starts to
solidify, like, you just

00:37:33.650 --> 00:37:35.340 align:middle line:90%
become rigid in every way.

00:37:35.340 --> 00:37:39.290 align:middle line:84%
So I think after this
journey, I started

00:37:39.290 --> 00:37:40.880 align:middle line:90%
trying to lean into that.

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:42.530 align:middle line:84%
If something makes
me uncomfortable,

00:37:42.530 --> 00:37:44.920 align:middle line:84%
trying to lean into it and
understand it and address it.

00:37:44.920 --> 00:37:46.045 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It takes courage.

00:37:46.045 --> 00:37:46.845 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:37:46.845 --> 00:37:49.550 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, I found it
very helpful, personally.

00:37:49.550 --> 00:37:51.420 align:middle line:84%
And in all the
literature I read,

00:37:51.420 --> 00:37:53.810 align:middle line:84%
it seems like that's
the best way forward.

00:37:53.810 --> 00:37:57.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So part
of your mission

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:00.320 align:middle line:84%
now is to help the
world of science

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:03.120 align:middle line:84%
and other scientists understand,
we've got to break free,

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:04.470 align:middle line:90%
we've got to open our minds.

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:07.640 align:middle line:84%
We've got to start
seriously researching

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:09.860 align:middle line:84%
these other modalities
even if it requires

00:38:09.860 --> 00:38:12.750 align:middle line:84%
creating new departments
with new kinds of science

00:38:12.750 --> 00:38:16.010 align:middle line:84%
and, also, speaking
to each other

00:38:16.010 --> 00:38:18.195 align:middle line:84%
because you've probably
come to understand

00:38:18.195 --> 00:38:20.570 align:middle line:84%
the mind is something far
different than what you thought

00:38:20.570 --> 00:38:20.980 align:middle line:90%
it was.

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:21.897 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Absolutely.

00:38:21.897 --> 00:38:24.170 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A lot of moving
parts there, permeating

00:38:24.170 --> 00:38:25.420 align:middle line:90%
every cell of the body.

00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:28.220 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yep, definitely.

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:29.970 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:38:29.970 --> 00:38:34.040 align:middle line:84%
So I was thinking,
how could I help,

00:38:34.040 --> 00:38:36.540 align:middle line:84%
because scientists are
really, really busy,

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:39.720 align:middle line:90%
and we usually don't have time.

00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:42.030 align:middle line:84%
If I'm a neuroscientist,
and I do cognitive work,

00:38:42.030 --> 00:38:44.610 align:middle line:84%
I usually don't even have time
to read something molecular,

00:38:44.610 --> 00:38:47.150 align:middle line:84%
much less something
way out there,

00:38:47.150 --> 00:38:49.460 align:middle line:90%
like metaphysical or spiritual.

00:38:49.460 --> 00:38:52.730 align:middle line:84%
So my collaborator and
I, Allison Paradise,

00:38:52.730 --> 00:38:54.950 align:middle line:84%
she's a neuroscientist
too, we thought,

00:38:54.950 --> 00:38:57.250 align:middle line:84%
what if we went
to the conference

00:38:57.250 --> 00:38:58.580 align:middle line:90%
that everyone goes to.

00:38:58.580 --> 00:39:02.450 align:middle line:84%
It's our Annual Society for
Neuroscience Conference.

00:39:02.450 --> 00:39:05.840 align:middle line:84%
It's the biggest in the field
and maybe even in science.

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:08.590 align:middle line:84%
It has 30,000 or 40,000
attendees every year.

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:10.400 align:middle line:84%
So they're already
going to this.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:11.900 align:middle line:90%
It's for their careers.

00:39:11.900 --> 00:39:13.160 align:middle line:90%
They're going to be there.

00:39:13.160 --> 00:39:18.310 align:middle line:84%
So what if we did a session
there and just created a space?

00:39:18.310 --> 00:39:21.055 align:middle line:84%
And we'll call it neuroscience
and spirituality or something

00:39:21.055 --> 00:39:21.855 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:39:21.855 --> 00:39:23.147 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: And see who shows up.

00:39:23.147 --> 00:39:24.355 align:middle line:90%
You're probably there with--

00:39:24.355 --> 00:39:26.355 align:middle line:84%
you have your little cups
of coffee on the side,

00:39:26.355 --> 00:39:29.100 align:middle line:84%
thinking two people will show
up, and thousands will show up.

00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:30.400 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:39:30.400 --> 00:39:31.580 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't thousands yet.

00:39:31.580 --> 00:39:34.670 align:middle line:84%
But I definitely thought,
no one was going to show up.

00:39:34.670 --> 00:39:38.420 align:middle line:90%
But we had a room filled.

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:39.950 align:middle line:90%
It was overflowing.

00:39:39.950 --> 00:39:42.035 align:middle line:84%
I think it was between
50 to 60 people.

00:39:42.035 --> 00:39:43.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And it
was overflowing.

00:39:43.410 --> 00:39:44.785 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: But it
was overflowing

00:39:44.785 --> 00:39:46.900 align:middle line:84%
because we got such a
small room because I

00:39:46.900 --> 00:39:48.380 align:middle line:90%
didn't think anyone would come.

00:39:48.380 --> 00:39:48.640 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:48.640 --> 00:39:50.060 align:middle line:84%
I was like, oh, no
one will come to this.

00:39:50.060 --> 00:39:51.020 align:middle line:90%
This will be fine.

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:54.920 align:middle line:90%
But it was standing room only.

00:39:54.920 --> 00:39:57.560 align:middle line:90%
And they all had questions.

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:02.320 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the topics were varied,
from precognitive dreams

00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:06.430 align:middle line:84%
to reincarnation to
psychedelics to just God

00:40:06.430 --> 00:40:08.210 align:middle line:90%
and religion and science.

00:40:08.210 --> 00:40:10.640 align:middle line:90%
And it was really great.

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:15.140 align:middle line:84%
So it motivated us
to do more of that.

00:40:15.140 --> 00:40:17.140 align:middle line:84%
And because a lot
of them told us,

00:40:17.140 --> 00:40:21.490 align:middle line:84%
they were surprised to see it
on the planner, the program

00:40:21.490 --> 00:40:23.320 align:middle line:84%
for the conference,
that they never

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:26.530 align:middle line:84%
see anything about
spirituality or consciousness

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:30.500 align:middle line:84%
at this conference, and that
they wanted to stay in touch,

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:33.350 align:middle line:84%
they wanted a group, they
wanted more references,

00:40:33.350 --> 00:40:34.580 align:middle line:90%
so we started all of that.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:37.912 align:middle line:84%
We started a website and
making a list of references.

00:40:37.912 --> 00:40:40.120 align:middle line:84%
We started Google group,
and we send out a newsletter

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:43.030 align:middle line:84%
once a month just to recommend
things for them to read.

00:40:43.030 --> 00:40:45.670 align:middle line:90%
And then we continue to do this.

00:40:45.670 --> 00:40:47.980 align:middle line:90%
So we started it in 2022.

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:50.530 align:middle line:84%
And we've done it
every year since then.

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:52.830 align:middle line:90%
And it's growing.

00:40:52.830 --> 00:40:56.010 align:middle line:84%
And people, it's becoming
more open to the space.

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:57.990 align:middle line:84%
Actually, when they
come, they share more.

00:40:57.990 --> 00:41:03.520 align:middle line:84%
And they're not as unsure about
themselves and what to say.

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:07.390 align:middle line:84%
They're more like, I'm a
molecular neurobiologist,

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:09.900 align:middle line:84%
but I'm also like
a Reiki healer,

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:13.590 align:middle line:84%
or I do neurodevelopmental
neurobiology,

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:16.888 align:middle line:84%
but I also can see
and hear spirits.

00:41:16.888 --> 00:41:19.180 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: This is much more
fabulous thing you've done.

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:21.120 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is the
beginning of the change,

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:22.720 align:middle line:90%
is the people like you.

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:25.230 align:middle line:84%
And I know the common
term or the popular term

00:41:25.230 --> 00:41:27.340 align:middle line:84%
is to be a disrupter,
but you actually are.

00:41:27.340 --> 00:41:29.650 align:middle line:90%
You're bringing in expanded--

00:41:29.650 --> 00:41:31.240 align:middle line:90%
it's more expansive.

00:41:31.240 --> 00:41:34.743 align:middle line:84%
And I'm very happy
that you chose this.

00:41:34.743 --> 00:41:36.160 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, you
were born to do it.

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:38.530 align:middle line:84%
So I have just one
final question.

00:41:38.530 --> 00:41:42.030 align:middle line:84%
And that is, with the
people coming in and some

00:41:42.030 --> 00:41:44.710 align:middle line:84%
of the brilliant new,
really young people,

00:41:44.710 --> 00:41:48.010 align:middle line:84%
the Gen Z's coming up in this
field, what are you seeing?

00:41:48.010 --> 00:41:51.490 align:middle line:84%
Are you seeing that they're
maybe a little more open or not?

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:52.495 align:middle line:90%
What's going on there?

00:41:52.495 --> 00:41:53.620 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah, of course.

00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:54.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because
we always think,

00:41:54.720 --> 00:41:56.512 align:middle line:84%
oh, they're going to
be open to everything.

00:41:56.512 --> 00:41:57.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah, it varies.

00:41:57.820 --> 00:42:00.810 align:middle line:84%
But I will say, this
year, man, there

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:02.140 align:middle line:90%
was this group that came in.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:05.230 align:middle line:84%
We were just so in love with
them because they were young.

00:42:05.230 --> 00:42:07.230 align:middle line:84%
They were first-year
graduate students.

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:10.080 align:middle line:84%
And they had brought their
undergraduate research

00:42:10.080 --> 00:42:11.050 align:middle line:90%
assistants with them.

00:42:11.050 --> 00:42:13.590 align:middle line:84%
It was a whole lab
that came together.

00:42:13.590 --> 00:42:17.280 align:middle line:84%
And they came late, but
they came with questions.

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:18.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, I love it.

00:42:18.490 --> 00:42:20.730 align:middle line:84%
>>SOBHANI: And they
had read stuff already.

00:42:20.730 --> 00:42:23.610 align:middle line:84%
And they just had the
most interesting questions

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:25.830 align:middle line:90%
and the most far out.

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:27.370 align:middle line:84%
They had already
made connections.

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:28.953 align:middle line:84%
They were like, what
part of the brain

00:42:28.953 --> 00:42:31.030 align:middle line:84%
is involved with
psychic phenomena?

00:42:31.030 --> 00:42:34.513 align:middle line:84%
How is trauma related to being
open to emergent experiences?

00:42:34.513 --> 00:42:36.180 align:middle line:84%
Allison and I were
just looking at them,

00:42:36.180 --> 00:42:38.400 align:middle line:90%
like, wow, they've arrived.

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:39.200 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:40.623 align:middle line:90%
So it was really exciting.

00:42:40.623 --> 00:42:41.790 align:middle line:90%
I hope we get more of those.

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:42.998 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah, you will.

00:42:42.998 --> 00:42:44.190 align:middle line:90%
You're absolutely will.

00:42:44.190 --> 00:42:46.890 align:middle line:84%
And so we just have
a minute or two left.

00:42:46.890 --> 00:42:50.040 align:middle line:84%
So any final thoughts on where
you think this might be going

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:53.180 align:middle line:84%
and just how the
experience of understanding

00:42:53.180 --> 00:42:55.730 align:middle line:84%
mind in a much
more expansive way

00:42:55.730 --> 00:42:58.690 align:middle line:84%
has just shifted your
complete reality?

00:42:58.690 --> 00:42:59.540 align:middle line:90%
>>SOBHANI: Yeah.

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:01.070 align:middle line:10%
So as I mentioned,
for me, it was

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:04.310 align:middle line:10%
philosophy that really
helped me blow open

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:06.750 align:middle line:10%
that prison in my own mind.

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:08.970 align:middle line:10%
So Allison and I are
trying to do that for them.

00:43:08.970 --> 00:43:11.120 align:middle line:84%
And I do think
that's key to making

00:43:11.120 --> 00:43:14.820 align:middle line:84%
them see your inside of
a box of your own making,

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:16.200 align:middle line:90%
of your own choice.

00:43:16.200 --> 00:43:18.510 align:middle line:10%
Yes, science
operates in that box.

00:43:18.510 --> 00:43:22.310 align:middle line:10%
But if we start looking at our
results and our study designs

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:26.000 align:middle line:10%
from other worldviews, it's
just a fun thought exercise

